post_text:
Revised Information on Pandemic EBT: Emergency School Meals Program

Family Income Survey no longer needed to qualify for the P-EBT benefit:

OPSI is partnering with the Department of Social and Health Services to provide help with food benefits as a result of the COVID-19 school closure. Oroville School District is a Community Eligibility Provision (CEP) district and all our students eat for free. All children enrolled in Oroville School District are automatically eligible to apply for P-EBT through DSHS.

If your family receives Basic Food—you will automatically receive P-EBT benefits on your existing EBT card. But all other families with children enrolled in Oroville School District will need to apply for P-EBT through DSHS at washingtonconnection.org. The deadline for the P-EBT application is August 26, 2020.

To read more about the Pandemic EBT Program, visit the link below: http://medium.com/waospi/washington-families-get-help-to-buy-food-during-school-closures-d6a1535570a

REMINDER:

We will be having an informational meeting on Nov 20th (TODAY) at 6pm in the High School Commons. We welcome any members of the community that have an interest in Oroville Students and Agriculture to please attend.

The Oroville FFA has been rechartered and we are looking for members of the community that would be interested in joining the Oroville FFA Alumni and Friends Booster Club. First established in 1969, alumni and booster programs provide parents, former members and those with a vested interest in agriculture and youth development with opportunities to assist with raising funds, recruitment, coordinating events and supporting FFA programs. Through our commitment to FFA and Agricultural Education, FFA Alumni help guide students in their communities down the path to success.

post_text:
Due to frozen pipes and a damaged fire suppression system this past winter, Oroville School District had to close school for one day (February 7, 2019). This one day will need to be made up to stay in compliance with State Law. We will be adding one day to the end of our present school calendar. Consequently, Friday, June 7th will be a regular full day of school and the last day of school will now be Monday, June 10th.

Despite our attempt at getting this day waiver through OSPI, Washington State Education Law states that each school district shall conduct a school year of no less than 180 school days in such grades as are conducted by the school district (WAC 180-16-215 ), and, a waiver was not granted.

Despite our attempt at getting this day waiver through OSPI, Washington State Education Law states that each school district shall conduct a school year of no less than 180 school days in such grades as are conducted by the school district (WAC 180-16-215 ), and, a waiver was not granted.

post_text:
Our dedicated board members share a common goal, to provide a positive learning environment for our children. We want to celebrate these everyday heroes-the five elected school board members who serve our students and the educational system. With deep care and compassion our board members put in a lot of hours focusing on the well-being of each student. Their time is spent attending extracurricular activities, professional development sessions, volunteering at school and community events.
During this month of recognition we ask you to show your appreciation for their service. Please show your gratitude in some way for their time, effort, and dedication to public education's advancement. Thank them for advocating on behalf of our collective interests and making the difficult decisions. Most importantly, thank them for being everyday heroes and making our students' success, their priority.
text:
Our dedicated board members share a common goal, to provide a positive learning environment for our children. We want to celebrate these everyday heroes-the five elected school board members who serve our students and the educational system. With deep care and compassion our board members put in a lot of hours focusing on the well-being of each student. Their time is spent attending extracurricular activities, professional development sessions, volunteering at school and community events.
During this month of recognition we ask you to show your appreciation for their service. Please show your gratitude in some way for their time, effort, and dedication to public education's advancement. Thank them for advocating on behalf of our collective interests and making the difficult decisions. Most importantly, thank them for being everyday heroes and making our students' success, their priority.

post_text: After several months of above average precipitation, the water table is very high. As a reminder: Floods can occur anywhere, with floodwaters rising gradually or flash floods striking suddenly. As a precaution please do not drive through standing water. The average automobile can be swept off the road in 12 inches of moving water, and roads covered by water are prone to collapse. Attempting to drive through water also may stall your engine, with the potential to cause irreparable damage if you try to restart the engine. If you come upon a flooded street, take an alternate route.

post_text:
NOTICE: WINTER MAKE UP DAY

Washington State Education Laws state that each school district shall conduct a school year of no less than 180 school days in such grades as are conducted by the school district. (WAC 180-16-215 )

Due to the amount of snow and ice this past winter, Oroville School District had to close school for one day (February 15, 2017). This one day will need to be made up to stay in compliance with State Law. We will be adding one day to the end of our present school calendar. Consequently, the last day of school will now be Monday, June 12th. Friday, June 9th will be a regular full day of school.

post_text: The second young cougar was treed on Tuesday, ironically enough, in the same tree as the other one the day before, across the river from the school. Both have now been relocated by the Fish and Game Department.
text: The second young cougar was treed on Tuesday, ironically enough, in the same tree as the other one the day before, across the river from the school. Both have now been relocated by the Fish and Game Department.

post_text: A couple of young cougars have been spotted in the area lately. Washington State Fish and Game had the hound dogs out this morning and located one across the river from the school. It was tranquilized and relocated. They are currently tracking another one south of town. Notifications have been sent out to parents via the K-12 Alerts system and both students and staff have been notified to be aware. http://wdfw.wa.gov/living/cougars.html#encounters

post_text:
Last Wednesday, the junior and senior high school band students participated in the NCW Music Educators Association Large Group Instrumental Music Festival held at Manson. The students performed brilliantly, and received the highest rating, Superior, from the judges.

These students comprise a wonderful team of musicians, and they represented our school district well in all that they did while at the festival. Needless to say, I am very proud of these students and so should we all! Please join me in congratulating them by at least giving them a virtual hug, or perhaps even a real high-five!

Have a great day!
Best regards,
Eric Stiles

post_text: This is Classified Employee Appreciation week. Classified employees are all the district employees who do not hold a teaching certificate including secretaries, bus drivers, custodians, cooks, librarians, maintenance, and paraeducators. We often take for granted the many support staff who often work quietly, efficiently, and behind the scenes to help each and every day at school run smoothly, which supports the learning of our students. Thank you for your hard work and dedication to our students. You make a difference each and every day! Thank you!

post_text: Spring Sports for students in grades 8-12 begin Monday, March 2nd. Please encourage your children to get involved and turn out for a sport. There are multiple options available in the Spring: Baseball, Softball, Track, Golf, Tennis, and Boys Soccer. 8th grade students can participate in all of these sports except track, which is offered to 7th and 8th grade students starting March 23rd. Please make sure all paperwork, including physical exams are completed before the first day of practice.

post_text:
Here is a great reminder from our school nurse, Glenda Harvey.

Flu Season is hitting our students and staff hard right now. Please take care of yourself and your children!

Please remember that FREQUENT HAND-WASHING is the best way to protect yourself. Hand sanitizers with alcohol are effective against Influenza, but not against Norovirus( "stomach flu".) EXTRA SLEEP AND FLUIDS are always a good idea during flu season.

Remind students to COVER THEIR COUGH WITH THEIR ELBOW instead of their hand.

Clean common surfaces with a disinfectant often.

Students with a fever should not return to school until temperature has been normal for 24 hrs without the use of fever reducing medication. If they have been vomiting, they should not return until 24 hrs after the last occurrence.

Starting Monday, January 5, 2015 - 3 Bus Routes will have changes:
Bus #1 (dog) - County 7
Bus #11 (cat) - Eastlake
Bus #12 (rabbit) - Westlake

Due to the fluctuation of students on bus routes and for safety reasons, we are making changes to 3 of the bus routes, starting Monday, January 5, 2015. The changes may effect the time that your student is picked up & dropped off. We have mailed out notices to the students that will be affected by the changes. Thank you for your cooperation and patience in the changes of the routes.

post_text:
Dear parents and/or guardians of students at Oroville Elementary School:

We are partnering with BrightBytes, an educational data analytics company, in order to learn more about our students’ school and home technology use for learning.

We are reaching out to ask you to take part in our Parent/Family questionnaire. Your participation is essential in helping us form a more complete picture of technology use for learning in our students’ lives. Please know that all of your responses will remain anonymous to protect your privacy and they will help your child's school choose the right technology for their classrooms. It will take approximately 5 minutes to complete.

We are hoping parents will complete this questionnaire by October 1st.

Please go to BBYT.ES and enter in the appropriate 5-character code below:

Elementary Parents: 887NP
Jr/Sr High School Parents: 2P4UP

Thank you for taking part in this important initiative!

post_text:
We are pleased to introduce a new, free reading service providing digital books through OverDrive (http://oroville.lib.overdrive.com).
Why OverDrive?
The OverDrive collection is an extension of our physical library, only it’s online with 24/7 access to eBooks and audiobooks. It’s convenient for students to check out titles anytime, anywhere with no worry about misplacing a book or running up late fees – these digital titles automatically return at the end of the lending period!

To use OverDrive, students browse the secure website for titles, borrow using your username and password, and enjoy on your computer, tablet, smartphone or eReader device. Usernames are generally firstname.lastname and passwords will be the student's lunch code. If you have problems, please see a librarian.

You can view our High School Library collection at the following site AND you can view both eBooks and physical books.
orovillehighschool.goalexandria.com

The elementary library can be found at...
orovilleelementary.goalexandria.com
